                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5663: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-03T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 3, 1933—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 3—1:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4. Nakayama<note n="5" xml:id="d2fn5">Shoichi Nakayama, First Secretary of the
                        Japanese Legation in China.</note> of Japanese Legation informed press
                    correspondents this morning that matter of clash at Shanhaikwan had been taken
                    out of Legation’s hands and was being handled by the Japanese Commandant at
                    Tientsin who was issuing orders to Commandant of Legation Guard here over
                    Legation’s head; that a letter was sent last night to Marshal Chang Hsueh-liang
                    demanding that he accept responsibility for clash at Shanhaikwan and that
                    situation was dangerous as Chinese were refusing to accept conciliatory
                    gestures. Shanhaikwan reported bombed by the Japanese.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
